==ACC vs other conferences==

===ACC vs Power 5 matchups===
The other Power 5 conferences ([[Big Ten Conference|Big 10]], [[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]], [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]], and [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]]) announced a conference-only schedule model, and no ACC team played another Power 5 team during the regular season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bigten.org/documents/2020/8/5//2020_B1GFB_Schedule.pdf?id=6806|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200805132918/https://bigten.org/documents/2020/8/5//2020_B1GFB_Schedule.pdf?id=6806|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 5, 2020|title=Big Ten Announces Plans for 2020 Football Season, Medical Protocols for All Sports|publisher=The Big Ten Conference}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sources: Big 12-approved scheduling model includes 9 conference games, 1 nonconference game |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/29591566/sources-big-12-approved-scheduling-model-includes-9-conference-games-1-nonconference-game |publisher=ESPN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pac-12.com/news/2020/7/31/pac-12-approves-2020-football-schedule-plans-fall-sports.aspx|title=Pac-12 approves 2020 football schedule & plans for fall sports|website=pac-12.com|publisher=Pac-12 Conference|date=July 31, 2020|access-date=August 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.secsports.com/article/29565989/sec-establishes-new-conference-only-football-start-date|title=SEC establishes new conference-only football start date|website=secsports.com|publisher=Southeastern Conference|date=July 31, 2020|access-date=August 7, 2020}}</ref>

